    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-02-20T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-02-20T08:00:00-05:00" n="489"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d489">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">320/2–2053: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Tunis</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_JJJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Jones</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d489fn1">This telegram was repeated to Paris, Cairo, London,
                        Algiers, Rabat, Naples, and Tripoli.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tunis</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-02-20T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >February 20, 1953—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>254. Tunis roundup.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Residency advises that Resident General has sent Grellet to Tunis [<hi
                            rend="italic">Paris?</hi>] for few days to assist Secretary General
                            <persName>Pons</persName> and Finance Director Fraisse in negotiations
                        for larger slice for Tunisia of French investment plan. Grellet will also
                        discuss election dates and arrangements with Foreign Office. Residency
                        source hinted to us today that caidal elections may be postponed until after
                            <hi rend="italic">ramadan</hi> (paragraph 3, Tunis telegram 250)<note
                            n="2" xml:id="d489fn2">
                            <ref target="#d488">
                                <ref target="#d488">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                                </ref>
                            </ref>.</note> since time required instruct rural population re voting
                        procedure. Same source said Neo Destour has instructed party members to
                        register for vote but to abstain election day, thus attempting prove that
                        Tunis capable voting but unwilling participate French-imposed
                        reforms.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Residency reportedly broadening its contacts among Tunisians who are
                        coming to it in greater numbers with expressions of friendship. At palace
                            <persName corresp="#p_SMB1">Ben Salem</persName> said to be advocating
                        accommodation with France and this has led to tension between him and Prince
                            <persName corresp="#p_BPC1">Chedly</persName>. In recent speech Tunis
                        audience, Resident General stated native population could only be good
                        friends of France if they were first good Tunisians. <hi rend="italic"
                            >Comment:</hi> This is good line.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Residency intelligence chief admitted today that resumption bomb incidents
                        source concern and that police have caught red-handed only one bomb-thrower
                        who said unknown man had given him 500 francs to carry parcel which resulted
                        in deaths two children (Tunis <pb facs="0906" n="860" xml:id="pg_860"/>
                        telegram 233).<note n="3" xml:id="d489fn3">Jan. 19, not printed. It reported
                            on incidents of violence during the previous weekend and said the
                            hypothesis of the Residency was that the Neo-Destour and <gloss
                                target="#t_UGTT1">UGTT</gloss> leaders had forbidden terrorism but
                            their discipline was inadequate to halt it. (772.00/1–1953)</note>
                        Pressed on point whether police had succeeded in establishing link between
                        bombings and Communists (paragraph 3, Tunis telegram 252),<note n="4"
                            xml:id="d489fn4">Feb. 16, not printed. It contained another report on
                            violence in Tunis. Paragraph 3 said the current theory was that the
                            incidents were the product of Communist exploitation of inexperienced
                            members of the Neo-Destour, whom the party was unable to control.
                            (772.00/2–1653)</note> source replied “we are without proof”. He said
                        also that while regular Tunisian Communists hold meetings and write letters,
                        their activities innocuous. Residency refuses them exit visas to attend
                        Communist conferences abroad, invitations to which are mailed here mostly
                        from Prague and Vienna.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Same source said investigation <persName corresp="#p_HF1"
                            >Hached</persName> murder stalled.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JJJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jones</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
